  <thing id="cuUWWrath1" name="Rage" description="You may enter a barbarian rage 1/day. If you already had the rage ability, you may rage one additional time per day. Every five levels thereafter, you gain an additional use of this ability (two rages at 5th, three at 10th, and so on)." compset="ClSpecial" summary="+4 Str, +4 Con, +2 to Will saves, -2 to AC when enraged.">
    <fieldval field="actName" value="Raging"/>
    <fieldval field="actName2" value="Fatigued"/>
    <usesource source="srcBookFnd"/>
    <tag group="User" tag="Tracker"/>
    <tag group="Usage" tag="DayRound"/>
    <tag group="User" tag="Activation"/>
    <tag group="ProductId" tag="HLCommunit"/>
    <tag group="AbilType" tag="Extra"/>
    <eval phase="PostLevel" priority="10000"><![CDATA[      ~ If we're not shown, just get out now
      doneif (tagis[Helper.ShowSpec] = 0)

      ~we get unholy warrior level rounds of rage/day
      field[trkMax].value += 1 + (round(#levelcount[UnholyWar]/5,0,-1)) + (hero.tagcount[HasFeat.fExtraRage] * 6)]]></eval>
    <eval phase="First" priority="450" index="2"><![CDATA[
      ~if we're curently raging, forward a tag to the hero.
      ~note the timing is just before First/500, which is when the containerreqs on the rage powers will look for this tag
      if (field[abilActive].value <> 0) then
        perform hero.assign[Hero.Raging]
        endif
      
      ~we count as having Rage for the purpose of feats
      perform hero.assign[HasAbility.cBbnRage]]]></eval>
    <eval phase="PostLevel" priority="10000" index="3"><![CDATA[~if barbarian rage is present, we're not needed
if (hero.tagis[Ability.cBbnRage] <> 0) then
  #trkmax[cBbnRage] += field[xAllLev].value
  perform assign[Helper.SpcDisable]
  perform delete[Helper.ShowSpec]
  done
  endif

      ~ If we're not shown, just get out now
      doneif (tagis[Helper.ShowSpec] = 0)

      ~ If we're enraged, apply the stat modifiers for that
      var level as number
      level = field[xAllLev].value
      var attrbonus as number
      var savebonus as number

        attrbonus = 4
        savebonus = 2

      if (field[abilActive].value <> 0) then
        hero.child[aSTR].field[Bonus].value += attrbonus
        hero.child[aCON].field[Bonus].value += attrbonus
        #applybonus[BonMorale, hero.child[svWill], savebonus]
        hero.child[ArmorClass].field[Penalty].value -= 2
        endif

      ~ Set up our text fields
      field[CustDesc].text = "Fly into a rage, giving you +" & attrbonus & " Str, +" & attrbonus & " Con, +" & savebonus & " to Will saves and -2 to Armor Class. Many skills and abilities cannot be used while the character is enraged.{br}{br}Rage lasts for 3 rounds + Con bonus."

        field[CustDesc].text = field[CustDesc].text & " At the end of the rage, the barbarian becomes fatigued (-2 Str, -2 Dex, can't charge or run) for the rest of the encounter."

      field[abSumm].text = "+" & attrbonus & " Str, +" & attrbonus & " Con, +" & savebonus & " to Will saves, -2 to AC when enraged."]]></eval>
    <eval phase="PostLevel" priority="10000" index="4"><![CDATA[
      ~ If we're not shown, just get out now
      doneif (tagis[Helper.ShowSpec] = 0)

        if (field[abilAct2].value <> 0) then
          hero.child[aSTR].field[Penalty].value -= 2
          hero.child[aDEX].field[Penalty].value -= 2
          perform assign[Helper.ChgDisab1]
          endif]]></eval>
    </thing>
  <thing id="ruDaeGlome" name="Daemon, Glomeray" description="Braggarts are common in any society. Many see themselves as the best their culture can create, fully versed in a number of languages, skills, or the best at a particular profession or some other role. Mortals can be gratuitous in their display of wealth and privilege, while others wear scandalous clothing to reveal their perfect bodies. Regardless of how pride manifests, the glomeray love these mortals best.\n\nThe glomeray encourage bad behavior by clustering around the shadows cast in their circle. They urge them to be proud of their accomplishments, to bask in their achievements and to take their rightful place in their societies. Simple pride in one&apos;s work is nothing if no one knows how good you really are. Of course, boasts and bragging tend to isolate these individuals, as other mortals rarely suffer such behavior for long. With their isolation, the glomeray seize more control over these mortals, further alienating them from others, until such time that despair sets in. The glomerays feel they have done their jobs well, when the mortal commits suicide.\n\nGlomeray rarely venture to the Material Plane, for they believe that their beauty would undermine their purpose and overshadow the minor successes of their chosen sinners. So, they content themselves with watching from afar. If summoned to the Material Plane, they are arrogant and petty, epitomizing the corruption of excessive pride.\n\nGlomerays use spell-like abilities and speed to defeat their enemies. They enjoy exulting in their victories, and often torment their opponents by engaging them in long discussions about the history of Gehenna and their pivotal role in it, while pulling their foes apart. They avoid “to-the-death” conflicts by flying away if outnumbered, counting the experience as instructional.\n\nGlomerays are five feet long, including their beautiful tail." compset="Race">
